  "value": "Medium",
  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight: it links discovered failures to model internals (neuron coverage / which neurons are activated) and to statistical failure patterns (which transformations and which sub-models produce more errors). The authors empirically show neuron-coverage changes correlate with output changes, demonstrate that different realistic transformations activate different neurons, and report per-model/per-transformation distributions of errors and false positives. However, the paper does not explain failures in terms of deeper underlying vulnerabilities (e.g., specific spurious features, dataset bias, or concrete causal mechanisms) nor does it provide root-cause analyses that identify why the model relied on non-robust features — only that certain inputs/transformations and neuron activations are associated with failures.",
  "evidence": "Page 304, (Introduction / contributions): \"We empirically demonstrate that changes in neuron coverage correlate with changes in an autonomous car’s behavior.\"; Page 308, Section 5 RQ1: \"This result indicates that the neuron coverage changes with the changes in output steering angles, i.e. different neurons get activated for different outputs.\" (Table 5, relation between neuron coverage and test output); Page 309, Section 5 RQ2 / Result 2: \"Result 2: Different image transformations tend to activate different sets of neurons.\" and \"These results indicate that for all models, except Chauffeur-LSTM, different transformations activate different neurons.\" (Figure 4 and accompanying text); Page 310, Section 5 RQ4 and Table 8: \"Interestingly, some models are more prone to erroneous behaviors for some transformations than others.\" and reporting per-model counts of erroneous behaviors for rain, fog, shear, etc.; Page 311, Section 5 RQ5 / Result 5: \"Accuracy of a DNN can be improved up to 46% by retraining the DNN with synthetic data generated by DeepTest.\" (shows remediation via data augmentation but not a causal explanation of underlying vulnerabilities)."
